# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1899-cleveland-spiders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1890 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 44–88 record and a seventh-place finish in the National League.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The team played six straight home games in Indianapolis, Indiana at Indianapolis Park between July 28 and August 2 against the Brooklyn Bridegrooms and New York Giants.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] It was a former Sunday-games ballpark of the Indianapolis Hoosiers who had folded at the end of the previous season.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1891 Cleveland Spiders season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished with a 65–74 record and a fifth-place finish in the National League.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders moved to a new ballpark in 1891.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] League Park was financed by Spiders owner Frank Robison, and it would be the team's home for the remainder of their existence.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] It would also be home to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] Patsy Tebeau, the team's starting third baseman, was named manager midway through the season.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] He remained the Spiders manager until his contract was reassigned to the St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1892 Cleveland Spiders**, led by star pitcher Cy Young, finished with a 93–56 overall record, second-best in the National League.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] In the first split season in Major League Baseball history, the Spiders finished in fifth place during the first half of the season, and in first place during the second half.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] After the season, they played against the first-half champions, the Boston Beaneaters, in the "World's Championship Series", which the Spiders lost, five games to none (with one tie).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The **1892 World Series** followed the first split season in National League history, with the first-half champion Boston Beaneaters (102–48) playing the second-half champion Cleveland Spiders (93–56) in a best-of-nine postseason series to determine the overall champion of the 1892 baseball season.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] After the first game ended in a 0–0 tie due to darkness, Boston won the next five games to win the championship.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Contemporary newspaper reports referred to the games as the "**World's Championship Series**" or "**World's Series**".
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] This was the last of the pre-modern-era World Series, and followed similar annual postseason competitions held from 1884 to 1890 between the champions of the National League and the American Association (which collapsed after the 1891 season).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Later, the Temple Cup would be awarded to the winner of an annual postseason series between National League teams, from 1894 to 1897.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Boston manager Frank Selee worried that late-October weather conditions would lead to postponements and low attendance.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Bookies had the Spiders as the favorite, due to their pitching staff.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Cy Young had gone 36–12 in 49 starts, with a 1.93 earned-run average.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Meanwhile, Boston star Mike "King" Kelly had a batting average of only .189 for the year, and was described as "one of the biggest failures of the base ball season".
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Hugh Duffy of Boston batted .462 with nine runs batted in and six extra-base hits including a home run.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Had the series required more than six games to complete, the remaining games would have been played in New York City.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The first game, which had started at three o'clock, had gone 11 scoreless innings when it was stopped at five o'clock due to darkness.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] After a travel day for the teams, the series moved to Boston with the Beaneaters leading, two games to none.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] John Clarkson started for Cleveland in place of Cy Young, who complained of a "lame arm".
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] After an off-day (professional baseball games were not allowed on Sundays in Boston until 1929) the Beaneaters won their fifth game of the series to capture the championship.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The 13 players on their roster split $1000 prize money.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The National League abolished the split season format for 1893, and did not play another split season until 1981, which was caused by a players' strike.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] John Clarkson had started the season with the Beaneaters, and signed with the Spiders after being released at the end of June.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Pitcher Lee Viau also played for both Boston and Cleveland during 1892.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The Beaneaters were later known as the Doves (1907–1910) and the Rustlers (1911) before adopting the nickname of "Braves" in 1912.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The franchise relocated to Milwaukee in 1953, and then moved to Atlanta in 1966, where they remain members of the National League as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The Spiders' final season was 1899, when they compiled a record of 20–134 (establishing a longstanding record for the worst major league season) after ownership moved their best players to the St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Louis Cardinals, and were one of four teams contracted out of the National League when the league reduced its size to eight teams prior to the 1900 season.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1899 Cleveland Spiders season** was the team's 13th and final season in Major League Baseball (MLB), and their 11th season in the National League (NL).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders' team owners, the Robison family, also owned the St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] To strengthen the Perfectos, they transferred the Spiders' best players to St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis before the season, leaving Cleveland with a severely depleted roster.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As the Spiders played abysmally and continued to lose that season, fans stopped attending their home games, and other teams refused to travel to Cleveland to play road games against the Spiders.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This resulted in the Spiders being forced to play most of their games on the road.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL, with a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This remains the worst single-season record for an MLB team in terms of both losses and of winning percentage (.130).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team allowed 1,252 runs while only scoring 529, a run differential of −723 for the season, the worst in MLB history.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Spiders pitchers hit 109 batters, setting an MLB single-season record that would stand for 123 years until the 2022 Cincinnati Reds hit 110 batters.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early 1899, the owners of the Spiders, brothers Frank and Stanley Robison, bought the St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis Browns baseball club from Chris von der Ahe, renaming it the Perfectos.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] However, they continued to retain ownership of the Cleveland club, an obvious conflict of interest that was later prohibited by MLB.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Robisons decided that a good team in St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis would draw more fans, so they transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, as well as manager Patsy Tebeau to St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Most of the players Cleveland received were non-entities.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Jack Clements (known to history as one of MLB's few left-handed throwing catchers) and Joe Quinn were at the end of successful careers, and player-manager Lave Cross was traded back to St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis after the Spiders got off to an 8–30 start.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They also transferred numerous home games to the road—including the original Opening Day game to St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, the Spiders did not play their first home game until May 1.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early April, the Spiders started training in Terre Haute, Indiana.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Because of the cold weather, the team had to practice inside a gymnasium.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] With a decimated roster, it was apparent almost from the start that the Spiders would make a wretched showing.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After a poor start on the road, the Spiders played a home-opening doubleheader on May 1 in front of 100 fans.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They split the two games, moving up to 11th place.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] However, they were back in last before long.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On June 2, the Spiders led the Brooklyn Superbas, 10–0, in the sixth inning, but they blew the lead and ended up losing, 11–10.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On June 11, the Spiders lost to the Cincinnati Reds, 10–1, behind Frank Bates' poor pitching.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] It was the Spiders' 11th straight loss on that road trip.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The following day, the Spiders returned home and lost to the Pittsburgh Pirates in front of 58 fans.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team kept losing games, and losses came more and more frequently as the season went on.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On August 16, with Bates pitching, the Spiders lost to the Superbas, 13–2.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This led to criticism from the *Cleveland Plain Dealer*.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On August 18, the first-place Superbas completed their sweep of the Spiders, outscoring them, 43–8, in four games.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders notched their 100th loss of the season on August 31, falling to the Superbas, 9–3.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Two days later, the Spiders played a local amateur team in Johnstown, Pennsylvania, and lost, 7–5.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On September 12, the Spiders lost both games of a doubleheader to the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] At that point, they were 19–114 and had broken the MLB single-season record for losses, which had been 113.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On October 15, the Spiders ended their season by losing both games of a doubleheader to the Cincinnati Reds, by scores of 16–1 and 19–3.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After losing 40 of their last 41 games, they had a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Their record is still the worst in Major League Baseball history.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They trailed the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas by 84 games, and finished 35 games behind the 11th place Washington Senators.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] For comparison, this would project to 21–141 under the current schedule, and Pythagorean expectation based on the Spiders' results and the current 162-game schedule would translate to a record of 25–137.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20 against the Phillies and May 21 against the Colonels.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They also accumulated the second-longest losing streak in league history, at 24 games from August 26 to September 16, trailing only the 26-game losing streak set by the 1889 Louisville Colonels.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders were winless against two teams: Brooklyn and Cincinnati.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The pitching staff allowed a record 1,252 runs in 154 games.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders batters combined to hit 12 home runs, matching former Spiders star Bobby Wallace, who hit 12 home runs for St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The 1899 Spiders did lead the league in one statistic—games played.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Cleveland was the only team in the league to finish all of its games in the then-154 game schedule of the 1899 season, a rather unusual occurrence in that era.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Due to poor attendance, the Spiders played 112 road games, as a result of 35 of their planned home games being moved.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early 1899, team Robison Brothers publicly announced their intention to run the Spiders "as a sideshow", and fans took them at their word: after the first 16 home games, Cleveland's total attendance was 3,179, for a trifling average of 199 people per game.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, other NL teams refused to travel to Cleveland's League Park, since their cut of the ticket revenue would not even come close to covering their travel and hotel expenses.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, the Spiders only played 26 more home games for the rest of the season, including only eight after July 1.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Their records of 112 road games and 101 road losses will never be threatened: it is currently unbreakable under MLB's current scheduling practices, where a team plays a maximum of 81 road games.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The only time it was even considered approachable was the aforementioned 1994 Mariners, but the strike of that season ended the possibility of them breaking the record, and no team has played more than 81 road games since then (not counting 1 or 3 game tiebreaker playoff games).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] A mere 6,088 fans paid for Spiders home games in 1899, an average of 145 people per game.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis drew 373,909 fans for their home season, including 15,000 for one game (their home opener against the Spiders).
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The dismal 1899 season was the end for the Spiders, and for National League baseball in Cleveland.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders were disbanded, along with the original Baltimore Orioles, the Louisville Colonels (Louisville, nor the entire state of Kentucky, has had another professional sports team since), and the original Washington Senators, as the National League contracted from 12 teams to 8.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The departure of baseball from Cleveland left an opening for the upstart American League, which opened for business in 1901 as a second major league and included among its charter members a new team, the Cleveland Blues.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Blues still exist today as the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Currently, the 2024 Chicago White Sox (121) has the post-1900 AL and MLB records for most losses in a season.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After the Spiders folded, a National League team would not play in Cleveland again until the Brooklyn Robins visited the then-Cleveland Indians in the 1920 World Series.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis, the Perfectos were renamed the St.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis Cardinals in 1900, which they are still called today.
[src:1899-cleveland-spiders-season/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Robisons purchasing of the Browns/Perfectos/Cardinals essentially began a turnaround for the organization, as they eventually became one of the most recognizable teams in baseball in the 20th century, appearing in 15 World Series and winning 9.
